### Optional Parameters

Parameters marked with `?` can be omitted when calling a function.

### Syntax

```typescript
function greet(name: string, greeting?: string): string {
  return `${greeting ?? "Hello"}, ${name}!`;
}

greet("Alice"); // "Hello, Alice!"
greet("Bob", "Hi"); // "Hi, Bob!"
```

### Type of Optional Parameters

An optional parameter's type is `T | undefined`:

```typescript
function log(value?: string): void {
  console.log(value); // type is string | undefined
}
```

### Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|------------|
| Must come after required | Optional params must follow required params |
| Default value | Can have default values (see default_params) |
| undefined passable | Explicitly passing undefined is allowed |

### Ordering

```typescript
// Correct
function fn(a: string, b?: number, c?: boolean): void {}

// Error: Optional params before required
// function fn(a?: string, b: number): void {}
```

### Callback Optional Parameters

```typescript
function fetchData(
  url: string,
  onSuccess?: (data: unknown) => void,
  onError?: (error: Error) => void
): void {
  // Implementation
}
```

> **Key Point:** Optional parameters are `T | undefined` at runtime but exclude `undefined` at the type level.

codeExample:
// Optional parameter
function createUser(name: string, age?: number, email?: string): object {
  return {
    name,
    age: age ?? 0,
    email: email ?? "unknown@example.com"
  };
}

console.log(createUser("Alice"));
console.log(createUser("Bob", 25));
console.log(createUser("Charlie", 30, "charlie@example.com"));

// Optional parameters in callbacks
function process(
  data: number[],
  onComplete?: () => void
): void {
  console.log(data);
  onComplete?.(); // Safe call with optional chaining
}
